CONTEXTUAL DEPLOYMENT VERIFIED
- The global upper-HUD DEPLOY button and its DOM event dependency are removed.
- A live hostile base must be selected directly on the map before the deployment action appears.
- The lower target panel identifies the exact hostile base and exposes one contextual deployment action.
- The deployment panel locks the selected hostile base and no longer contains a second hostile-target selector.
- Combat missions offer only combat-capable squad types; retrieval squads are excluded from hostile-base deployment.
- Available recovery items expose direct GPS collection and a separate retrieval-squad deployment action.
- Recovery deployment locks the selected item and offers only the retrieval squad.
- Successful dispatch closes the deployment panel; dispatch validation, resource use and ready-squad reuse remain canonical.
- Target panels are height-limited and their action rows remain visible without covering most of the map.
- Wide-screen deployment is side-aligned; mobile deployment is height-limited and positioned above the defense toolbar.

ISSUES FOUND AND CORRECTED
1. The upper HUD opened a global target list, weakening the relationship between a map target and the resulting attack order. The global entry point was removed.
2. The old deployment modal allowed selecting a different hostile base after the player had already selected one on the map. The target grid was removed and the map-selected target is now immutable for that operation.
3. Removing the global button would have orphaned remote recovery. Available recovery items now expose their own contextual recovery-squad action.
4. The lower target UI could occupy excessive map area. Target-specific context now has a strict viewport-height ceiling, sticky actions and landscape side positioning.
5. The deployment overlay obscured too much of the tactical map. It now uses a compact side panel on wide screens and a toolbar-aware height limit on narrow screens.
6. Obsolete deployment-button references, generic target-selection handlers and unused local values were removed rather than retained as compatibility layers.

